    <%- include('partials/navbar', { page: 'timeline' }) %>

    <main class="container mt-4">
        <h1 class="display-4 text-center mb-5"> Timeline - <b>Brief</b> Palestinian History </h1>

        <div class="timeline-container">
            <!-- Balfour -->
            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <img src="https://cdn.glitch.global/fc1f5b86-1bec-45c3-8173-cf4f62a73ef5/99775e59-0f9a-4014-8b4c-d6263fe73cff.image.png?v=1743932810217" style="max-width:600px; margin: left;" alt="Balfour declaration">
                  <small>
                    British soldiers patrol the streets of Jerusalem during a visit by Arthur James Balfour, a British Conservative politician, on April 2, 1925.
                    [Topical Press Agency/Hulton Archive/Getty Images]
                  </small>
                  <br>
                  <br>
                    <h2> 
                    <span class="year">1917</span> 
                    <span class="event-title">Balfour Declaration</span> 
                  </h2>
                    <p>The Balfour Declaration was a public statement by the British government during WWI supporting a "national home for the Jewish people" in Palestine. The 
                  declaration was signed by Arthur Balfour, a British foreign Secratary, who "offered sympathy" to the Jewish Zionist's aspriations. Zionism was a political
                  colonial movement that emerged in <b>Europe</b> in the 19th century that sought to create a Jewish national home in Palestine, which was inhabited by
                  Palestinians.
                    <br> With the help of the British, Zionists were able to migrate Jews from Europe to inhabited Palestine. 
                    <br>
                    <small>@ProgressiveInternational</small>
                  </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <!-- Nakba -->
            <div class="timeline-item">
                 <div class="timeline-content">
                    <img src="https://cdn.glitch.global/fc1f5b86-1bec-45c3-8173-cf4f62a73ef5/49dfef48-397e-4e89-b81f-70368f0a8477.image.png?v=1743934739015" style="max-width:600px; margin: left;"alt="Nakba">
                   <small> On May 15, 2017, Palestinians marked 69 years since the ethnic cleansing of Palestine [Reuters]</small>
                   <br>
                   <br>
                     <h2> 
                       <span class="year">1948</span>
                       <span class="event-title">Nakba</span> 
                   </h2>
                    <p>The Nakba, <b>"Catastrophe"</b>, refers to the mass displacement and dispossession of Palestinians in 1948.
                    In November 1947, the UN passed a resolution to expand Zionist territory from 6% currently conqured to 56% of historic Palestine.
                    The Zionist movement launched 'Plan Dalet'to kick Palestinians by any means necessary, resulting in 80% of Palestinians colonized.
                    <br>
                    The State of Israel was declared on this territory on May 14th 1948
                    <br>
                    15,000 Palestinians were killed in the Nakba by Israel militias, who also,
                    <li>expelled 750,000+ Palestinians</li>
                    <li>destroyed 531 Palestinian villiages/towns/cities</li>
                    <li>Committed up to 155 massacres</li>
                     <br>
                      The Nakba also refers to the <b>ongoing colonization of the remainder of Palestine</b>.
                   </p>
                   <small>@LetsTalkPalestine</small>
                 </div>
            </div>
             <!-- Six-Day War -->
             <div class="timeline-item">
                 <div class="timeline-content">
                    <img src="https://cdn.glitch.global/fc1f5b86-1bec-45c3-8173-cf4f62a73ef5/6a7e968d-9b54-4a99-855a-5a0d6afd2487.image.png?v=1744742904756" style="max-width:600px; margin: left;" alt="six-day war">
                    <h2>
                      <span class="year">1967</span> 
                      <span class="event-title">Six-Day War</span>
                   </h2>
                    <p>
                      Egypt, Syria, and Jordan rallied together against Israel when threats were made against them. Egypt believed that Arab 
                      unification 
                      Israel captured the Gaza Strip, the West Bank, East Jerusalem, Sinai Peninsula, and Golan Heights in this brief conflict
                      
                      
                      
                    </p>
                 </div>
            </div>
             <!-- Oslo Accords -->
             <div class="timeline-item">
                 <div class="timeline-content">
                    <img src="https://cdn.glitch.global/fc1f5b86-1bec-45c3-8173-cf4f62a73ef5/e779e921-7696-4e16-a3ad-fc24c4a4477d.image.png?v=1743938468140" style="max-width:600px; margin: left;"alt="Oslo Accords">
                   <small>A demonstrator from Deir Jarir waves a Palestinian flag following a march against construction on Palestinian land 
                     by residents of the Jewish settlement of Ofra, occupied West Bank, April 26, 2013. (Issam Rimawi/Flash90)</small>
                   <br>
                   <br>
                    <h2> 
                      <span class="year">1993</span>
                      <span class="event-title">Oslo Accords</span>
                   </h2>
                    <p> The Oslo Accords are mulitple agreements between Israel and the PLO aiming to establish some sort of negotiations. 
                   Within the agreements, Israel maintains control of the borders, security, and authority over imports/exports, and overall
                  Palestinian connection with the outside world.
                      <br>
                  The Oslo Accords were established to be a framework for future negotiations, intending to last 5 years. 30 years later, a final agreement hasn't
                  been reached and Israeli control is still in full force. 
                    <br>
                    <br>
                  The Oslo Accords claims to give Palestinians a governing body with the 'Palestinian Authority', yet Israel has full authority,
                  <br>
                  <br>
                  <b>"The Oslo Accords were never representative of the Palestinians people's demands... The Accords need to be dismantled
                  and identified for what they truly are...a unilateral legitmation of illegal occupation" </b> <small>@LetsTalkPalestine</small>
                   </p>
                 </div>
            </div>
            <!-- Second Intifada -->
             <div class="timeline-item">
                 <div class="timeline-content">
                    <img src="https://cdn.glitch.global/fc1f5b86-1bec-45c3-8173-cf4f62a73ef5/c551e18a-9445-43d8-8f12-e7a0f2d38d7c.image.png?v=1743934044396" style="max-width: 600px; margin: left;" alt="Second Intifada">
                   <small>What began as a few hundred protesters throwing shoes at Sharon, police escort erupted into demonstrations across the Palestinian territories [GALLO/GETTY]</small>
                    <h2> 
                      <br>
                      <span class="year">2000 - 2005</span> 
                      <span class="event-title">Second Intifada</span> 
                   </h2>
                    <p> The Second Intifada, meaning the "uprising" in arabic, was the second mass Palestinian uprising against the Israeli occupation. It was sparked on September 28th 2000 when 
                   Israeli politician Ariel Sharon, 1,000 armed Israeli soldiers, and police staged an "inprecedented, provactive visit to <b> Al Aqsa Mosque Compound</b> - 
                  one of Islam's holiest sites, - where Ariel Sharons declared: "The Temple Mount is in our hands and will remain in our hands" 
                      <br>
                  Palestinians defended Jeruslaem from the settler army, on September 30th, a parallel uprising began in Gaza in support of these protesters, 
                      <b>marking the Second Intifada</b>
                      <br>
                      4,000 to 5,000 Palestinians were killed during the Second Intifada
                      <br>836 children killed
                      <br>576 students killed 
                      <br>8,600 imprisoned, 288 of them being children
                      <br>3,530 disabled or maimed
        
                   </p>
                 </div>
            </div>
